<DOC><DOCNO> AP891011-0189 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2044EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-PuertoRico-Hugo     10-11 0268</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Puerto Rico-Hugo,0276</SECOND><HEAD>Red Cross Reports 26 Hurricane Deaths in Puerto Rico, Virgin Islands</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Hurricane Hugo killed 26 people inPuerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands when it swept through thearea in September, the American Red Cross said Wednesday.   The figure brings to at least 74 the total number known deadfrom the hurricane, which devastated several Caribbean islands aswell as parts of the Carolinas.   The Red Cross said in a release that 18 people died in PuertoRico and eight died in the Virgin Islands, including five on theresort island of St. Croix and three on nearby St. Thomas.   Previous reports indicated 14 had died in Puerto Rico and threein the Virgin Islands.   The numbers include those killed during the storm Sept. 17-18and subsequent hurricane-related deaths, such as injured victimswho later died and power linesmen killed while repairing downedlines, said Red Cross spokeswoman Susan Clowe.   The storm also killed 11 in Guadeloupe, 11 in Montserrat, one inSt. Kitts and 25 in North and South Carolina, authorities have said.   The release also said the Red Cross has served more than 7million meals in Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands since thehurricane struck, including 113,000 Tuesday.   It said 217 Red Cross shelters were currently housing 10,458people in the two territories, down from 21,168 housed right afterthe passage of Hugo.   About 15,000 homes were destroyed and 35,000 damaged in PuertoRico, the release said.   The Virgin Islands government estimated 90 percent of homes weredestroyed or damaged on St. Croix.</TEXT></DOC>